 Here we see $6+\frac{1}{2n+\frac{1}{6+\frac{1}{2n+\frac{1}{6+\cdots}}}} i.e. P = 6+\frac{1}{2+P}$</think>
$\Longrightarrow P=6+\frac1{2+P}$
$\Longrightarrow P^2-8P-12=0$, for which we can see
\begin{align} 
P = \frac{8\pm \sqrt{8^2-(-12*4)}}{2}=\frac{8\pm 4\sqrt{7}}{2}=4\pm 2\sqrt{7}
\end{align}
Since $P$ comes out to be positive, it is clear $P = 4+2\sqrt{7}$ (either root) $\Longrightarrow a=4, b=2, c=7\Longrightarrow a+b+c=13$
As you can see, the thought process is quite elaborate and time consuming too.
